Intent Signals Across Your Full-Funnel Strategy
Different intent signals matter at different stages of the buying process. Building a mature intent recognition strategy means understanding how signals evolve as prospects progress.

Top of Funnel Intent Signals

Early-stage prospects demonstrate intent through broader behavioral signals: downloading industry reports, attending educational webinars, following your brand on social media, or subscribing to your newsletter. These prospects may not know you exist yet, but they're actively researching challenges your solution addresses. In 2026, using intent platforms to find similar companies to your best customers and reaching them with relevant problem-focused content has become standard practice.

Mid-Funnel Intent Signals

As prospects move into active evaluation, their intent signals become more specific. They download solution-focused content, request product demonstrations, participate in sales calls, visit your pricing page, and engage with your customer success team. They're comparing options, conducting vendor research, and assessing fit. This is where Account Based Marketing truly shines—using accumulated intent signals to personalize every interaction and address specific needs.

Bottom-Funnel Intent Signals

Deep in the consideration stage, intent signals indicate urgency and commitment. Proposals requested, contract terms discussed, security assessments conducted, and reference checks initiated all signal imminent purchase decisions. Sales teams that recognize these signals and respond with appropriate acceleration tactics see 25-30% improvements in deal closure rates.

The Role of Industry-Specific Intent Signals
Intent signals vary meaningfully across industries, and sophisticated B2B marketers customize their intent frameworks accordingly.

For healthcare organizations, intent signals might include visits to HIPAA compliance pages, downloads of case studies from similar health systems, inquiries about integration with specific EHR systems, and questions about regulatory requirements. Someone at a health system researching these topics is signaling they're actively solving compliance challenges.

In the IT and cybersecurity space, intent might manifest through searches for zero-trust architecture, downloads of threat landscape reports, exploration of specific threat detection features, and engagement with content addressing current vulnerabilities. When a CISOs team collectively engages with your advanced threat protection content, you've found active intent.

For HR technology buyers, intent signals include visits to compliance topic pages, engagement with competitor comparison content, questions about specific payroll integrations, and downloads of ROI calculators demonstrating efficiency gains. These signals paint a picture of an HR team actively evaluating upgrades.

Progressive companies in fintech, martech, and manufacturing similarly recognize that industry context shapes which signals matter most. Building intent recognition models tailored to your specific industry produces significantly better results than applying generic frameworks. 

